V-P-C, C-I-D-R, and subnets.

A V-P-C is region-scoped: it spans every availability zone in a region. Subnets, by contrast, are availability-zone-scoped. You pick an I-P-v-four C-I-D-R block at creation, anywhere from a slash-sixteen, which is sixty-five thousand addresses, down to a slash-twenty-eight, which is sixteen, and you can add secondary C-I-D-R blocks later if you outgrow it. A couple of planning rules. C-I-D-Rs must not overlap with anything you intend to peer with, so use ten-dot-zero, ten-dot-one, ten-dot-two for distinct environments, not the same block three times. The R-F-C nineteen-eighteen private ranges are conventional, but any range routes. And every account gets a default V-P-C per region, with one-seventy-two-dot-thirty-one, a public subnet per zone, and an Internet Gateway attached; it's fine for experiments and wrong for production.

A subnet is a slice of the V-P-C C-I-D-R confined to one availability zone. Crucially, the labels public and private are not properties of the subnet. They're a consequence of its route table. A subnet is public because its route table has a route to an Internet Gateway, and private because it doesn't. Re-associate it with a different route table, and its identity flips.

One gotcha: AWS reserves five I-P addresses in every subnet, the first four and the last one. So a slash-twenty-four gives two hundred fifty-one usable addresses, not two hundred fifty-six. That bites when you size a small subnet for a Lambda attachment or an interface endpoint and find yourself short.
